node.text:
The Trailer for Next's Opening menu in 2011. Paris 1906 Escoffier.
This menu was incredibly fun for us to create. We had to make some hard decisions on how closely we wanted to replicate Escoffier's recipes. He didn't have a high-speed blender to make a pureed soup but rather used a tammis. Which should we do? Was it more important to execute it exactly as he did over 100 years before or the most delicious?
On the current Next: 10th Anniversary Menu, which is available for indoor dining now, book on @tockhq we included the Supremes de Poussin course with a sidecar of Foie Gras ala Strasbourg.

node.text:
I decided the traditional step of trussing wasn’t the best technique when roasting a whole Turkey if the goal was keeping the white meat moist while trying to get enough heat down into the leg joint that typically stays pink to bloody until well after the white meat become dry from the direct heat. If you are ok challenging convention to achieve a better cooked Turkey overall give it a try.

This is part of a longer version of the Thanksgiving Meal Kit Demo we will post closer to the holiday to help guide you through the Alinea feast available for purchase from the link in my Bio.
#Alinea

node.text:
This week’s employee spotlight is Emily Chanhnourack, The Alinea Group’s Host Manager. Emily joined as a Host at The Aviary in May 2015 and was promoted to an Aviary FOH Manager two years later. Earlier this summer, Emily took on the role of TAG Host Manager, where she oversees host operations and trains and develops our growing team. 
Link in my bio to apply to The Alinea Group.

And more about Emily below.

What was the experience like when you first joined The Alinea Group? “I started off as a host at The Aviary and didn’t know much about cocktails or fine dining. I very quickly liked the culture and wanted to learn more. There was so much to learn!. Everyone had such a vast and technical knowledge about spirits, cocktails and food. We had a lot of training sessions - every week we’d talk through a drink on the menu, try the components separately, then learn how everything goes together.”

What are you looking forward to in your new role? “This role excites me because I helped create it – I saw a need for a Host Manager and it felt like a role where I could do the things I was best at. Now I get to help other people like me who weren’t as experienced. I’m excited to train, develop and guide people, helping them to get the most out of their job.”

What is your most memorable experience at TAG? “The Aviary book project and watching it come to life. We witnessed the whole creative process and it was a cool moment when we saw the final product at the book release party. Everyone was so excited.”

What activities do you enjoy outside of work? “Eating and drinking, and seeing live music and shows. Also, hanging out with my two cats and spending time with my family.”

Today, we are starting a new series to highlight members of our team at The Alinea Group. If you are interested in joining our team, RSVP to our Job Fair at The Aviary on Thursday, 7/8 (link in bio). 

Meet Rizqi, the General Manager at Alinea.
 
In 2014, Rizqi moved from California to Chicago to join our team at Next. He worked his way from Runner to Backwaiter to Front Waiter to Captain to Expeditor. He transferred to Alinea as an Expo and was promoted to General Manager in 2019. Learn more about Rizqi below:
 
What was your first restaurant job? "I started working at a local sushi joint back in California. My first task was to learn to mix wasabi!"
 
What is your most memorable experience at TAG? "My experience as an Expeditor was the most impactful and the most challenging. It allowed me to understand how to connect with both the FOH and BOH and the importance of team unification. As an Expo at Alinea, I had the opportunity to support our pop-ups in Madrid, and Miami, and Minneapolis. I experienced both humbling failures and great successes in that role which taught me to push forward positively, regardless of the outcome."
 
What is the best part of your job? "The "Aha" moments for both guests and colleagues. Feeling the support of an amazing service team. Watching the magic of a menu transition. Evolution, growth and the chemistry of teams and team members. Experiencing the joy of working in this industry and manifesting the same joy for our guests on a nightly basis."
 
What is your favorite activity on your days off? "I like to be moving and eating on my days off (not at the same time). I love to travel when time permits, ride my bike and general self care - you only have one body! Health is wealth!"

Thank you for your passion and leadership Riz!
